Parents, Relatives and Friends of Caseville Public School Athletes and Coaches,

With the 2020-2021 sports season now underway, there are some different protocols that we will be using at our sporting events both for players and for fans. To avoid confusion, here is the process that we will use for our fans.

First, each player and coach is allowed to bring no more than 2 fans to each game. So, a day or two before a home or away game, the coach or athletic director will give 2 ‘tickets’ to each player and coach. The player will write their name on the tickets and then give them to the fans that will be attending the game. Fans will write their name on the ticket as well. Upon arrival to…

ATTENTION EAGLE ATHLETES:

We are excited to announce there will be a football and volleyball season this fall. Several details regarding this are still developing, and we are in communication with coaches, the NCTL, and MHSAA. This is what we currently know:

Athletes will be required to have face masks and personal water bottles, water will not be available via drinking fountains or cups.

Physicals are NOT required for fall athletes. If a physical was done the prior school year, the student is eligible to play.

Online sports schedules will be updated as soon as we have finalized them with the NCTL. (North Central Thumb League)

Please be sure as a player or parent you are in communication…

link:
By now you should have received a mailing that included our calendar and bell schedule. Here are a few clarifications that we would like to point out:

1. School will dismiss early on Fridays at 1:50pm. (Unless it is scheduled as a half day on the calendar.)

2. The regular school day Monday through Thursday will go from 8:00am to 3:00pm.

3. All scheduled half days will run from 8:00am to 11:20am.

Please be sure you are aware of these changes and please share this post to help us spread the word.

post_text:
Today a committee of staff, administration, and a board member had a Return to School Planning Session to work on our COVID-19 Preparedness and Response Plan. Basic guidelines were discussed to be compliant with the MI Safe Schools 2020-2021 Return to School Roadmap but more specific details on day to day processes will be planned out with subcommittees over the next few weeks. These details will then need to be approved by the School Board and Huron ISD. Upon approval, they will be made available on our website seven days prior to the start date of school or August 17, whichever comes first. We will also be looking for parent input in a survey we hope to release by Friday. Please be on the lookout for this survey, your input is important to us as we plan ahead.

link:
Today a committee of staff, administration, and a board member had a Return to School Planning Session to work on our COVID-19 Preparedness and Response Plan. Basic guidelines were discussed to be compliant with the MI Safe Schools 2020-2021 Return to School Roadmap but more specific details on day to day processes will be planned out with subcommittees over the next few weeks. These details will then need to be approved by the School Board and Huron ISD. Upon approval, they will be made available on our website seven days prior to the start date of school or August 17, whichever comes first. We will also be looking for parent input in a survey we hope to release by Friday. Please be on the lookout for this survey, your input is important to us as we plan ahead.

Thank you for your patience and understanding as we work together to ensure a plan is set in place that works best for all involved. If you have questions or concerns in the meantime, administration is available via phone call to meet your needs.

Thank you and GO EAGLES!

We are looking for individuals, businesses or organizations interested in sponsoring or co-sponsoring some of our future POP UP PANTRY Events!! ‼️

Today is the the first time in over a decade that I have not lead the Caseville Band in our community Memorial Day Services. The students and I prepare and perform every concert with care, in service to our community, but none is as important or close to our hearts as our Memorial Day performances. That’s because on Memorial Day we are not performing for those that are listening in the audience. Instead, on this day, we are making music for those who are notably not in attendance with us. We sound our horns and clamor the drums on earth in the hopes that the sound will reach the heavens and let them know that despite their absence, they are never forgotten. We may not be able to gather… More

post_text:
The Summer EBT for Children (SEBTC) program will be providing free, healthy groceries to students eligible for free and reduced-price school meals this summer. Eligible students in our district will receive an SEBTC card pre-loaded with $30 worth of nutritious foods per summer month (June, July and August). Healthy foods such as milk, eggs, fresh fruits and vegetables are included in the food package. Families can use the SEBTC card in any WIC authorized store across Michigan.
SEBTC is a program of the Michigan Department of Health and Human Services, Women, Infants and Children (WIC) program, in collaboration with Michigan Department of Education. SEBTC has been funded by the USDA. For more information about which districts have been chosen or the program, visit www.sebtc-mi.com.

column1: Caseville Community Food Pantry will be partnering with Caseville United Methodist Church and many private donors to sponsor a POP UP PANTRY in CASEVILLE!!
TIME: Starting no later than 11:00 a.m.
Here are some useful tips to make food delivery easy and to adhere to physical distancing protocols.
➡️ Line up Northbound on VINE Street
➡️Arrive at least 1 or 2 hours before start time
➡️Have your trunk or hatch cleaned out and with container or boxes for food to be put in.
Please share this information with anyone in need of food assistance.

Keep in mind there is also a POP UP PANTRY every Saturday at Laker's Elementary and Monday's in Port Austin. We hope that ours in Caseville helps fill the gap for anyone who can't make it to either of these other PANTRY events.

ATTENTION:

Caseville Public School is excited to announce we will begin free weekly meal pick up for all children! Please help us by getting the word out! Here are the details:

1. Meal pick up will be done on Saturdays from 10AM-12PM curbside at Caseville Public School. Your school age child(ren) will receive five breakfast and five lunch meals for the following week.

2. Orders must be placed Tuesday of each week by noon (12PM) Simply email Mrs. Glaza, our Food Service Director and let her know how many children you are ordering food for. Caseville Community Food Pantry
April 14 at 3:51 PM ·

We got off to a late start but quickly made up time with the help of Braun Builders and their SkyTrak!

The weather was less than favorable too! Sun, clouds, wind, snow and sleet all made an appearance today. 🌞☁️🌬❄️🌨🌤 #PureMichigan

Our volunteers were amazing and they worked so hard to make sure the line moved at a good pace. 🦸🏻‍♀️🦸🏼

We made several deliveries to home bound individuals too and they were very happy for our help. 🚗🚚

Special thanks to Kurt E Damrow, Braun Builders, Caseville Public School and their amazing teachers and staff, our pantry volunteers, Caseville Police and Fire Department, DJ’s Portable Toilets and the many folks that showed up to lend a hand. This couldn’t have happened without you. 💕💕💕💕💕💕💕💕💕💕💕💕💕💕💕

Stay connected to our page for information on other pop up pantries occurring in our area. Remember- every Saturday in April, there will be a food drive at Laker Elementary. 🥒🥖🍗🍝🍪

As Caseville’s School Social Worker, Joe Pratt wanted to reach out and let you know that he will continue to be available to help address concerns for our students and/or families. Here is a message from him:

If there are needs I can help address please feel free to contact me. I won’t claim to have all the answers but, I can help connect you to available resources in our community. I can also be available to talk with your child on the phone, email, text, or video conference to address concerns or just to vent. If you would like to contact me, you can email me at jdpratt@huronisd.org or you can call my office phone at 989-269-3448 if you leave a voicemail I will receive an alert and I can call you back as soon as possible.

On April 2, 2020, Governor Whitmer issued Executive Order 2020-35 which effectively closed all K-12 school buildings for the remainder of the 2019-20 school year. Under this order, school districts are expected to develop a “Continuity of Learning Plan” so that students can continue to learn from home. Currently, our teachers have developed and communicated plans individually with students and parents. They have utilized different ways to communicate such as Skyward, Classtag and Google Classrooms.

In order for our teachers to properly communicate with you, it is important that your current email is up to date in Skyward. If you would like to update your email, please email Mrs. Sancrant at…

post_text:
Due to the uncertainty over COVID-19 and the Governor’s executive order closing all school buildings for the remainder of the academic year we have had to make the difficult decision to cancel the Caseville Band’s Little Cesar’s Pizza Kit Fundraiser in order to assure the safety of our students and their families. We are currently working on solutions for how we will be refunding money in a manner that assures the safety of our community members as well as our staff. If you paid for your order by check, those checks have not been deposited and will not be cashed. Please make a note of this for your personal records. If you paid by cash, we ask for your patience as we try to determine the safest and most efficient way to return your money. Thank you for your support. Please be safe and stay healthy!

GO EAGLES!

Good Morning from Miss S! Life In quarantine has been tricky for myself & my family. We have been surviving though. It is amazing what being stuck at your house can do for the kids! The kids have built a fort in our very small woods area. We have put a 2000 piece Disney puzzle together & colored. My kids have learned how to play a golf card game, yahtzee, pictionary air & lots more. It has been a much needed bonding time so far. Of course we have been doing school work & practicing for the upcoming baseball/softball seasons!

Good Morning from Miss S! Life In quarantine has been tricky for myself & my family. We have been surviving though. It is amazing what being stuck at your house can do for the kids! The kids have built a fort in our very small woods area. We have put a 2000 piece Disney puzzle together & colored. My kids have learned how to play a golf card game, yahtzee, pictionary air & lots more. It has been a much needed bonding time so far. Of course we have been doing school work & practicing for the upcoming baseball/softball seasons!

I miss all your smiling faces! I hope through this time of being limited, you all use your imaginations while playing, are being respectful to your parents & siblings. Helping around the house & keeping your brains moving!

Caseville Community Food Pantry
March 26 at 4:06 PM ·

IMPORTANT ANNOUNCEMENT!!

We will be doing curbside service again Friday March 27, 2020.

This is for our existing clients that have not yet been served in the month of March.

This is also for Caseville Schools student families that did not get served last week. Student families are asked to visit us every other week so we can make sure all families get served.

We will also serve new clients residing in Caseville, Caseville Township and Lake Township. Please bring ID.

Our volunteers are working hard to make sure service to our clients, student families and new clients is equitable. Please be patient with us as we work out a few kinks in the system.

Thank you for your support of our Community Food Pantry.🌸🌷💐

Caseville Community Food Pantry
March 20 at 6:29 PM ·

The words are hard to find at this moment because Thank You just seems too simple to express how we feel right now.

With the help of school teachers, Superintendent Ken Ewald and local citizens, we served more than 170 individuals from 70 households within Caseville, Caseville Township, Lake township and Caseville School families!

We plan to follow this format for the coming weeks.

If you know of someone that needs home delivery, please contact the Caseville United Methodist Church at 989-856-4009.

Again, thank you.

shared_text:
Caseville Community Food Pantry
March 16 at 3:32 PM ·

In light of the recent developments regarding the Corona virus or COVID 19 and Governor Whitmer issueing a State of Emergency for the State of Michigan, we want to assure all of our clients that we intend to operate as usual until circumstances force a change.

We are working closely with Caseville Public School to bring in those families that need food and meal assistance while school is closed as well as acquiring food from them that would otherwise go unused.

Delivery service can be arranged for those who are home bound or do not have transportation to the pantry.

As a reminder, we serve residents of Caseville, Caseville Township and Lake Township. Proof of residency in the form of a Driver's License or State issued ID is required as well as information regarding family income.

We are working on contingency plans if we can not serve clients face to face as we have been doing. We will be sure to keep everyone posted of any changes as soon as we can.

Thank you for constant support and may this crisis pass us with little or no effect. 🌺

Caseville Public Schools
March 13 at 9:54 AM ·

As many of you are aware, Gov. Whitmer had mandated our school to close starting Monday, March 16th out of caution due to COVID-19 prevention. The school building will be completely closed to students after today until we return. This includes all extracurricular activities.

Teachers will prep students today in class on what the next three weeks will look like. Our plan is to provide extracurricular packets that focus on building/maintaining basic skills. If your child is absent today, please be sure to come to the school to pick up their packet and locker items.

We also encourage you to remain calm during this time and continue to follow procedures outlined by our local health department…

Thank you every one!

The Caseville High School Drama Department proudly presents "The 39 Steps" opening on Friday, March 13th at 7PM with shows on Saturday, March 14th at 7PM and Sunday, March 15th at 2PM.

Doors open 30 minutes before curtain and General Admission tickets are $10 each

Mix a Hitchcock masterpiece with a spy novel, add a dash of Monty Python and you have The 39 Steps, a fast-paced whodunit for anyone who loves the magic of theater! This two-time Tony® and Drama Desk Award-winning treat is packed with nonstop laughs, over 150 zany characters (played by a ridiculously talented cast of 10), an onstage plane crash, villains, Scottish accents, and some good old-fashioned romance! Please share!

NOTICE OF BOARD VACANCY

If the majority of the Board is still seated, the vacancy shall be filled by the Board using the following procedure:

A. The Board shall seek qualified and interested candidates from the community through the media, word of mouth, and or contacts with appropriate organizations.

B. All applicants are to submit a notice of their interest, in writing, to the Board President.

C. Appointment by the Board to fill vacancy shall be by majority vote of the full Board.

Our middle and high school Robotics Teams performed well at the Regional Robotics Competition Saturday! Here are some highlights!

1. The high school had a team comprised of Katie McCormick, Pinkney Barrios, Lyssa Tucker and Julias Errer that made it to finals!

2. The middle school teams brought home two trophies!

* The Judges Award was earned by Grace Wilton, Michael Norkiewicz, Nathan Diehl, Maleighya Thompson and Nathan Burns.

*The highest honor of the day, the Excellence Award was given to the best all-around team, Samantha Harder and Kaila Love! Sam and Kaila will be competing a the state level March 1st!

The trophies will be displayed in the office, Congratulations to all!

GO EAGLES!

post_id:
To honor the life of Mrs. Janet Watts and her dedication to Caseville Public School, we will not have school this Friday, January 31. Mrs. Watts worked 42 years in education, as a teacher, counselor, and elementary principal, and retired from Caseville Public School. She had a strong passion for our students and staff and didn't hesitate to serve them in any way she was able. She will be greatly missed.

Funeral services will be held at 11:00am on Friday, January 31st, here at our school auditorium with Rev. Karen Bouverette officiating. Burial will be in Caseville Twp Cemetery. A Celebration of Life luncheon will follow the service at Seasons Change Home Health 8201 Port Austin Rd, Pigeon.

The Coming Home Game against CPS and festivities will still be held Friday evening and we encourage all to attend.

Please share, thank you.

PLEASE READ, WE NEED YOUR HELP!

We are excited to announce that we will now be "Honoring a Veteran" at each home game this winter.

In order to do this, we need your help! In the comments below, or through messenger, please nominate a Veteran you feel should be honored at a home game and why.

We are so proud of the brave men and women who have served our Country and are so excited to introduce them to our fans at sporting events!
